\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (a) The Court of Appeals was correct in refusing to enforce the 1 ppm exposure limit on the ground that it was not supported by appropriate findings. OSHA's rationale for lowering the permissible exposure limit from 10 ppm to 1 ppm was based not on any finding that leukemia has ever been caused by exposure to 10 ppm of benzene, and that it will\'a0
\f0\i not
\f1\i0 \'a0be caused by exposure to 1 ppm, but, rather, on a series of assumptions indicating that some leukemia might result from exposure to 10 ppm, and that the number of cases might be reduced by lowering the exposure level to 1 ppm. Pp.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#630"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 630}}-638.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (b) By empowering the Secretary to promulgate standards that are "reasonably necessary or appropriate to provide safe or healthful employment and places of employment" as required by \'a7 3(8), the Act implies that, before promulgating any standard, the Secretary must make a finding that the workplaces in question are not safe. But "safe" is not the equivalent of "risk-free." A workplace can hardly be considered "unsafe" unless it threatens the workers with a significant risk of harm. Therefore, before the Secretary can promulgate\'a0
\f0\i any
\f1\i0 \'a0permanent health or safety standard, he must make a threshold finding that the place of employment is unsafe in the sense that significant risks are present and can be eliminated or lessened by a change in practices. This requirement applies to permanent standards promulgated pursuant to \'a7 6(b)(5), as well as to other types of permanent standards, there being no reason why \'a7 3(8)'s definition of a standard should not be deemed incorporated by reference into \'a7 6(b)(5). Moreover, requiring the Secretary to make a threshold finding of significant risk is consistent with the scope of his regulatory power under \'a7 6(b)(5) to promulgate standards for "toxic materials" and "
\f0\i harmful
\f1\i0 \'a0physical agents." This interpretation is supported by other provisions of the Act, such as \'a7 6(g), which requires the Secretary, in determining the priority for establishing standards, to give due regard to the urgency of the need for mandatory safety and health standards for particular industries or workplaces, and \'a7 6(b)(8), which requires the Secretary, when he substantially alters an\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 Page 448 U. S. 609\cf0 \strokec3 \
