\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 existing consensus standard, to explain how the new rule will "better effectuate" the Act's purposes. Pp.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#639"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 639}}-646.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (c) The Act's legislative history also supports the conclusion that Congress was concerned not with absolute safety, but with the elimination of significant harm. Pp. 646-652.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 (d) Where the Secretary relied on a special policy for carcinogens that imposed the burden on industry of proving the existence of a safe level of exposure, thereby avoiding his threshold responsibility of establishing the need for more stringent standards, he exceeded his power. Pp.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#658"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 658}}-659.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
