\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Apart from its exclusion of gasoline storage and distribution facilities (an exclusion retained in the final rule,\'a0
\f0\i see
\f1\i0 \'a0text, at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#F25"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 n}}\'a025,\'a0
\f0\i infra
\f1\i0 ), the proposed rule also excluded from coverage work operations in which liquid mixtures containing 1% or less benzene were used. After a year, this exclusion was to be narrowed to operations where 0.1% benzene solutions were used. The rationale for the exclusion was that airborne exposures from such liquids would generally be within the 1 ppm limit. However, testimony at the hearing on the proposed rule indicated that there was no "consistent predictable relationship" between benzene content in a liquid and the resulting airborne exposure. Therefore, OSHA abandoned the idea of a percentage exclusion for liquid benzene in its final standard. 43 Fed.Reg. 5942 (1978).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 OSHA later reconsidered its position and, in an amendment to the permanent standard, reinstated an exclusion for liquids, setting the level at 0.5%, to be reduced to 0.1% after three years,\'a0
\f0\i id.
\f1\i0 \'a0at 27962.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#T23"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Footnote 23}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The exemption from the monitoring and medical testing portions of the standard for workplaces with benzene exposure levels below 0.5 ppm was not predicated on any finding that regulation of such workplaces was not feasible. OSHA's consultant, Arthur D. Little, Inc., concluded that 1 ppm was a feasible exposure limit even assuming that there was no action level (or, to put it another way, assuming that the action level was zero). Rather, it was, as NIOSH witnesses stated, a practical decision based on a determination that, where benzene exposures are below 0.5 ppm, they will be unlikely ever to rise above the permissible exposure level of 1 ppm. NIOSH was also concerned that, in the absence of an action level, employers who used sophisticated analytical equipment might be required to monitor and provide medical examinations simply because of the presence of benzene in the ambient air. Tr. 1030-1032, 1133-1134.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#T24"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Footnote 24}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Indeed, in its explanation of the standard OSHA states that an employer is required to institute engineering controls (for example, installing new ventilation hoods) even if those controls are insufficient, by themselves, to achieve compliance and respirators must therefore be used as well. 43 Fed.Reg. 5952 (1978). OSHA's preference for engineering modifications is based on its opinion that respirators are rarely used properly (because they are uncomfortable, are often not properly fitted, etc.), and therefore cannot be considered adequate protective measures.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#T25"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Footnote 25}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It is also inapplicable to work operations involving 0.5% liquid benzene (0.1% after three years),\'a0
\f0\i see
\f1\i0 \'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#F22"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 n}}\'a022,\'a0
\f0\i supra,
\f1\i0 \'a0and to the handling of benzene in sealed containers or systems, except insofar as employers are required to provide cautionary notices and appropriate employee training.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
