\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The structure of the separate subsection describing emergency temporary standards, 29 U.S.C. \'a7 655(c), quoted in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#F13"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 n}}\'a013,\'a0
\f0\i supra,
\f1\i0 \'a0supports this conclusion. It authorizes the Secretary to bypass the normal procedures for setting permanent standards if he makes two findings: (A) that employees are exposed to "grave danger" from exposure to toxic substances, and (b) that an emergency standard is "necessary" to protect the employees from that danger. Those findings are to be compared with those that are implicitly required by the definition of the permanent standard -- (A) that there be a significant -- as opposed to a "grave" -- risk, and (b) that additional regulation is "reasonably necessary or appropriate" -- as opposed to "necessary." It would be anomalous for Congress to require specific findings for temporary standards but to give the Secretary a\'a0
\f0\i carte blanche
\f1\i0 \'a0for permanent standards.\
