\cf0 MR. JUSTICE MARSHALL states that our view of \'a7 3(8) would make the first sentence in \'a7 6(b)(5) superfluous. We disagree. The first sentence of \'a7 6(b)(5) requires the Secretary to select a highly protective standard once he has determined that a standard should be promulgated. The threshold finding that there is a need for such a standard in the sense that there is a significant risk in the workplace is not unlike the threshold finding that a chemical is toxic, or a physical agent is harmful. Once the Secretary has made the requisite threshold finding, \'a7 6(b)(5) directs him to choose the most protective standard that still meets the definition of a standard under \'a7 3(8), consistent with feasibility.\
