\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 "What we were trying to do in the bill . . . was to say that, when we are dealing with toxic agents or physical agents, we ought to take such steps as are\'a0
\f0\i feasible
\f1\i0 \'a0and\'a0
\f0\i practical
\f1\i0 \'a0to provide an atmosphere within which a person's health or safety would not be affected. Unfortunately, we had language providing that anyone [
\f0\i sic
\f1\i0 ] would be assured that no one would have a hazard. . . ."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 "It was an unrealistic standard. . . ."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 116 Cong.Rec. 37622 (170), Legislative History,\'a0
\f0\i supra
\f1\i0 \'a0at 502 (emphasis added). Senator Dominick's objection to the "unrealistic" standard of the forerunner of \'a7 6(b)(5) does not imply that he thought \'a7 3(8) of the Act lacked substantive content.\'a0
\f0\i See post
\f1\i0 \'a0at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#710"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 710}}-711 (MARSHALL, J., dissenting). The Senator hardly would have proposed that \'a7 6(b)(5) be deleted entirely,\'a0
