\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This is not to say that the Secretary is prohibited from examining relative costs and benefits in the process of setting priorities among hazardous substances, or that systematic consideration of costs and benefits is not to be attempted in the standard-setting process. Efforts to quantify costs and benefits, like statements of reasons generally, may help to promote informed consideration of decisional factors and facilitate judicial review.\'a0
\f0\i See Dunlop v. Bachowski,
\f1\i0 \'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/421/560/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 421 U. S. 560}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/421/560/#571"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 421 U. S. 571}}-574 (1975). The Secretary indicates that he has attempted to quantify costs and benefits in the past.\'a0
\f0\i See
\f1\i0 \'a043 Fed.Reg. 54354, 54427-54431 (1978) (lead);\'a0
\f0\i id.
\f1\i0 \'a0at 27350, 27378-27379 (cotton dust).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It is not necessary in the present litigation to say whether the Secretary must show a reasonable relation between costs and benefits. Discounting for the scientific uncertainty, the Secretary expressly -- and reasonably -- found such a relation here.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
