\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It is useful to compare the Act with other regulatory statutes in which Congress has required a showing of a relationship between costs and benefits or of an "unreasonable risk." In some statutes, Congress has expressly required cost-benefit analysis or a demonstration of some reasonable relation between costs and benefits.\'a0
\f0\i See
\f1\i0 \'a033 U.S.C. \'a7 701a (Flood Control Act of 1936); 42 U.S.C. \'a7 7545(c)(2)(b) (1976 ed., Supp. II) (Clean Air Act); 33 U.S.C. \'a71314(b)(4)(b) (1976 ed., Supp. II) (Clean Water Act). In others, Congress has imposed two independent requirements: that administrative action be "feasible" and justified by a balancing of costs and benefits,\'a0
\f0\i e.g.,
\f1\i0 \'a043 U.S.C. \'a71347(b) (1976 ed., Supp. II) (Outer Continental Shelf Lands Act); 42 U.S.C. \'a7 6295(a)(2)(D) (1976 ed., Supp. II) (Energy Policy and Conservation Act). This approach demonstrates a legislative awareness of the difference between a feasibility constraint and a constraint based on weighing costs and benefits.\'a0
\f0\i See infra
\f1\i0 \'a0at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#719"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 719}}-720. In still others, Congress has authorized regulation of "unreasonable risk," a term which has been read by some courts to require a balancing of costs and benefits.\'a0
\f0\i See, e.g., Aqua Slide 'N' Dive Corp. v. Consumer Product Safety Comm'n,
\f1\i0 \'a0569 F.2d 831 (CA5 1978) (construing 15 U.S.C. \'a7 2058(c)(2)(A) (Consumer Product Safety Act));\'a0
\f0\i Forester v. Consumer Product Safety Comm'n,
\f1\i0 \'a0182 U.S.App.D.C. 153, 559 F.2d 774 (1977) (construing 15 U.S.C. \'a71261(s) (Child Protection and Toy Safety Act)).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#T4/28"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Footnote 4/28}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The plurality also relies on its perception that, if the "reasonably necessary" clause were not given the meaning it ascribes to it, there would be no guidance for "standards other than those dealing with toxic materials and harmful physical agents."\'a0
\f0\i Ante
\f1\i0 \'a0at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#640"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 640}}, n. 45. For two reasons, this argument is without force. First, even if the "reasonably necessary" clause does have independent content, and even if that content is as the plurality describes it, it cannot, under any fair-minded reading, supersede the express language of \'a7 655(b)(5) for toxic substances and harmful physical agents.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Second, as noted above, an earlier version of the bill applied the "no employee will suffer" language to all substances. At that time, there was no "gap," and accordingly it could not be argued that the "reasonably necessary or appropriate" clause had the content the plurality ascribes to it. In this light, the plurality's reasoning must be that, when Congress amended the bill to apply the strict \'a7 655(b)(5) requirements only to toxic substances, the definitional clause gained an independent meaning that in turn comprehended all standards. But surely this argument turns congressional purposes on their head. It reasons that, when Congress singled out toxic substances for special regulation, it simultaneously created a more lenient ("reasonably necessary") test for standards generally, and that, once that more lenient test was applicable, it somehow superseded the strict requirements for toxic substances. That reasoning is both illogical and circular. Nor is there any basis for the plurality's suggestion,\'a0
\f0\i see ante
\f1\i0 \'a0at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#649"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 448 U. S. 649}}, n. 54, that the original bill's application to all standards was "entirely inadvertent."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/448/607/#T4/29"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Footnote 4/29}}]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
